SECOND REGULAR SESSION
HOUSE COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE FOR
HOUSE BILL NOS. 2120 & 1698
103RD GENERAL ASSEMBLY
4303H.04C JOSEPH ENGLER, Chief Clerk
AN ACT
To repeal section 160.775, RSMo, and to enact in lieu thereof one new section relating to
school antibullying policies.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the state of Missouri, as follows:
Section A. Section 160.775, RSMo, is repealed and one new section enacted in lieu
2 thereof, to be known as section 160.775, to read as follows:
160.775. 1. [Every district shall adopt an antibullying policy by September 1, 2007]
2 This section shall be known and may be cited as "Sawyer's Law".
3 2. As used in this section, the following terms mean:
4 (1) "Act of school violence" or "violent behavior", the same meaning as in
5 section 160.261;
6 (2) "Bullying" [means], intimidation, unwanted aggressive behavior, or harassment
7 that is repetitive or is substantially likely to be repeated and causes a reasonable student to
8 fear for his or her physical safety or property; substantially interferes with the educational
9 performance, opportunities, or benefits of any student without exception; or substantially
10 disrupts the orderly operation of the school. Bullying may consist of physical actions,
11 including gestures, or oral, cyberbullying, electronic, or written communication, and any
12 threat of retaliation for reporting of such acts. Bullying of students is prohibited on school
13 property, at any school function, or on a school bus[.];
14 (3) "Crime", any of the crimes listed in section 160.261;
15 (4) "Cyberbullying" [means], bullying as defined in this subsection through the
16 transmission of a communication including, but not limited to, a message, text, sound, or
17 image by means of an electronic device including, but not limited to, a telephone, wireless
18 telephone, or other wireless communication device, computer, or pager;
EXPLANATION — Matter enclosed in bold-faced brackets [thus] in the above bill is not enacted and is
intended to be omitted from the law. Matter in bold-face type in the above bill is proposed language.

HCS HBs 2120 & 1698 2
19 (5) "Zero-tolerance disciplinary policy", a policy or practice of discipline that
20 results in an automatic disciplinary consequence against a student without the discretion
21 to modify such disciplinary consequence on a case-by-case basis, such as automatic
22 detention, suspension, or expulsion or the automatic imposition of other disciplinary
23 measures.
24 3. Each schooldistrict's and charter school'santibullying policy shall be founded on
25 the assumption that all students need a safe learning environment. Policies shall treat all
26 students equally and shall not contain specific lists of protected classes of students who are to
27 receive special treatment. Policies may include age-appropriate differences for schools based
28 on the grade levels at the school. Each such policy shall contain a statement of the
29 consequences of bullying.
30 4. Each schooldistrict's and charter school'santibullying policy shall be included in
31 the student handbook and shall require, at a minimum, the following components:
32 (1) A statement prohibiting bullying, defined no less inclusively than in subsection 2
33 of this section;
34 (2) (a) A [statement] procedure requiring school district or charter school
35 employees to report any instance of bullying of which the employee has firsthand knowledge.
36 (b) The [policy] procedure shall require a school district or charter school
37 employee who witnesses an incident of bullying to report the incident to the school district's
38 or charter school's designated individual at the school [within two school days] in a timely
39 manner of the employee witnessing the incident, provided that such incident is reported
40 before the end of the school day if such incident occurred within the school day, or
41 before the beginning of the next school day if such incident occurred outside of
42 operational hours of the school.
43 (c) The procedure shall require that the parent or legal guardian of the bullied
44 student be notified of the bullying incident at the same time the incident is reported and
45 the investigation has started;
46 (3) A statement relating to victims of bullying that the school district or charter
47 school prohibits, does not have, and will not adopt, in name or in practice, a zero-
48 tolerance disciplinary policy;
49 (4) A statement relating to pupils who engage in self-defense that the school
50 district or charter school administration, when determining disciplinary action for a
51 pupil who has committed an act of school violence or exhibited violent behavior, will
52 take into account if such act of school violence or violent behavior was committed in self-
53 defense as an immediate response to an act of school violence or violent behavior
54 committed against such pupil;

HCS HBs 2120 & 1698 3
55 (5) A procedure for reporting an act of bullying. The policy shall also include a
56 statement requiring that the school district or charter school designate an individual at each
57 school building in the district and charter school to receive reports of incidents of bullying.
58 Such individual shall be a school district or charter school employee who is teacher level
59 staff or above;
60 [(4)] (6) A procedure for prompt investigation of reports of violations and complaints,
61 identifying one or more employees responsible for the investigation including, at a minimum,
62 the following requirements:
63 (a) Within two school days of a report of an incident of bullying being received, the
64 school principal, or his or her designee, shall initiate an investigation of the incident and
65 ensure that the report is reduced to writing;
66 (b) The school principal may appoint other school staff to assist with the
67 investigation; [and]
68 (c) The investigation shall be completed within ten school days from the date [of the
69 written report] the investigation is initiated under paragraph (a) of this subdivisionunless
70 good cause exists to extend the investigation; and
71 (d) A written report shall be prepared that contains the results of the
72 investigation and any response including, but not limited to, a description of any
73 interventions, initiatives, techniques, or discipline provided to all involved individuals of
74 the incident. The school district or charter school may develop a standardized form to
75 use for such written report;
76 [(5)] (7) A procedure for the response to any investigation that finds an act of
77 bullying occurred. The policy shall, at a minimum, require notifying the parents of the
78 bullying student;
79 (8) A statement that prohibits reprisal or retaliation against any person who reports an
80 act of bullying and the consequence and appropriate remedial action for a person who
81 engages in reprisal or retaliation;
82 [(6)] (9) A statement of how the policy is to be publicized; and
83 [(7)] (10) A process for discussing the district's antibullying policy with students and
84 training school employees and volunteers who have [significant] contact with students in the
85 requirements of the policy, including, at a minimum, the following statements:
86 (a) The school district or charter school shall provide information and appropriate
87 training to the school district or charter school staff who have [significant] contact with
88 students regarding the policy including, but not limited to, training on the appropriate
89 interventions staff may take and the associated liability for action or inaction including,
90 but not limited to, failure to report incidents;

HCS HBs 2120 & 1698 4
91 (b) The school district or charter school shall give annual notice of the policy to
92 students, parents or guardians, and staff;
93 (c) The school district or charter school shall provide education and information to
94 students regarding bullying, including information regarding the school district or charter
95 school policy prohibiting bullying, the harmful effects of bullying, and other applicable
96 initiatives to address bullying, including student peer-to-peer initiatives to provide
97 accountability and policy enforcement for those found to have engaged in bullying,
98 reprisal, or retaliation against any person who reports an act of bullying;
99 (d) The administration of the school district or charter schoolshall instruct its school
100 counselors, school social workers, licensed social workers, mental health professionals, and
101 school psychologists to educate students who are victims of bullying and students
102 committing acts of bullying on techniques for students to overcome bullying's negative
103 effects. Such techniques shall include, but not be limited to, cultivating the student's self-
104 worth and self-esteem; teaching the student to defend himself or herself assertively and
105 effectively; helping the student develop social skills; or encouraging the student to develop an
106 internal locus of control. The provisions of this paragraph shall not be construed to contradict
107 or limit any other provision of this section; and
108 (e) The administration of the school district or charter school shall implement
109 programs and other initiatives to address bullying, to respond to such conduct in a manner
110 that does not stigmatize the victim, and to make resources or referrals available to victims of
111 bullying and students committing acts of bullying.
112 5. Notwithstanding any other provision of law to the contrary, any school district or
113 charter school shall have jurisdiction to prohibit cyberbullying that originates on a school's
114 campus or at a district activity if the electronic communication was made using the school's
115 technological resources, if there is a sufficient nexus to the educational environment, or if the
116 electronic communication was made on the school's campus or at a school district or charter
117 school activity using the student's own personal technological resources. The school district
118 or charter school may discipline any student for such cyberbullying to the greatest extent
119 allowed by law.
120 6. Each school district and charter school shall review its antibullying policy and
121 revise it as needed. The school district's school board or charter school's governing board
122 shall receive input from school personnel, students, and administrators when reviewing and
123 revising the policy.
124 7. (1) The administration of each school district and charter school shall report
125 to the school board or governing board all acts of bullying, acts of school violence or
126 violent behavior, and crimes that occurred in between board meetings and the discipline

HCS HBs 2120 & 1698 5
127 of any pupil who committed such acts. Such report shall be submitted monthly and
128 shall be formatted to clearly describe each such incident.
129 (2) The school board or governing board shall review such monthly report in a
130 closed meeting under chapter 610. Discrepancies in such report shall be resolved within
131 thirty days of the review and the board, in conjunction with the school administration,
132 shall attempt to address and resolve substantiated concerns relating to incidents listed
133 on such report, as concerns are expressed during such monthly review by school
134 administration or school board or governing board members.
135 8. (1) A school district or charter school employee or volunteer may, in the
136 course of fulfilling duties or performing services for such school district or charter
137 school, intervene in an incident involving an act of bullying, act of school violence or
138 violent behavior, or crime committed against a pupil to protect such pupil.
139 (2) Such school district or charter school employee or volunteer shall be held
140 harmless and immune from any liability for actions described in subdivision (1) of this
141 subsection if:
142 (a) In the course of intervening in such incident, such employee or volunteer
143 follows a proper procedure for such interventions adopted by the school board of such
144 school district or the charter school's governing board; or
145 (b) Such employee or volunteer intervenes in good faith and in a manner that
146 such employee or volunteer reasonably believes is afforded the defense of justification
147 under chapter 563.
148 9. (1) A school district or charter school, or an employee of such district or
149 charter school, that in good faith imposes disciplinary action under this section upon a
150 bullying student shall not be civilly liable for such disciplinary action.
151 (2) If a school district or charter school, or an employee of such district or
152 charter school, prevails in an action brought against such school district, charter school,
153 or employee described in subdivision (1) of this subsection, the court shall award court
154 costs and attorney's fees to such prevailing school district, charter school, or employee.
155 10. (1) This section shall not be construed to provide immunity from liability for
156 a school district's or charter school's denial, or the denial by an employee of such
157 district or charter school, of any constitutionally protected right of a student.
158 (2) Subdivision (1) of this subsection shall not be construed to limit any
159 immunities or defenses available under state or federal law to a school district, a charter
160 school, or employees or volunteers of such school district or charter school.
161 11. (1) For the purposes of reporting requirements under section 210.115,
162 incidents of bullying, acts of school violence or violent behavior, or crime may be
163 considered abuse.

HCS HBs 2120 & 1698 6
164 (2) No provision of this section shall be construed to preclude any person from
165 reporting such abuse and such person shall be afforded the same protections provided
166 under sections 210.135 and 210.145 for reports of abuse in compliance with section
167 210.115.
168 12. No charter school shall expel or transfer a student to a school district solely
169 due to reports of bullying made against such student.
